#DESCRIPTION
# Series.  Convergence
#ENDDESCRIPTION

#KEYWORDS('Series' , 'Convergence' )

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(2,9,1);
$b = random(2,9,1);

BEGIN_TEXT
Find the value of the integral 
\[ \int_2^{\infty} \frac{dx}{$a x (\ln($b x))^2}. \] $BR
\{ans_rule(20)\} $BR
Determine whether the series $BR
\[ \sum_{n=2}^\infty \frac{1}{$a n (\ln($b n))^2} \] $BR
is convergent. Enter C if the series is convergent, D if the series is divergent. \{ans_rule(2)\}
END_TEXT

$b2 = $b*2;

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOF'));
$SOL $BR
First evaluate the indefinite integral. 
Make the substitution \(u=\ln($b x)\), 
\(\displaystyle du=\frac{1}{$b x}$b dx = \frac{dx}{x}\). 
$BR 
Then \(\displaystyle \int \frac{dx}{$a x (\ln($b x))^2} = 
\frac{1}{$a}\int \frac{du}{u^2} = - \frac{1}{$a u} + C = 
- \frac{1}{$a \ln($b x)} + C \). 
$BR
Now, \(\displaystyle \int_2^{\infty} \frac{dx}{$a x (\ln($b x))^2} = 
\lim_{t\to\infty} \int_2^t \frac{dx}{$a x (\ln($b x))^2} \)
$BR 
\(\displaystyle =  \lim_{t\to\infty} 
\left( - \frac{1}{$a \ln($b t)} + \frac{1}{$a \ln($b\cdot 2)} \right) =
\frac{1}{$a \ln($b2)} \). 
$PAR
By the integral test, since the integral is convergent, the series is convergent.
EOF

$ans1 = 1/($a*ln(2*$b));
$ans2 = "C" ;
ANS(num_cmp($ans1));
ANS(str_cmp($ans2));

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
